<p>China’s Commerce Ministry said it does not want a tariff war but is &quot;not afraid&quot; of one, accusing the United States of &quot;double standards&quot; and warning of &quot;corresponding&quot; or &quot;resolute&quot; measures if Washington proceeds with new trade barriers [euronews.com#1][thehindu.com#2][dw.com#5][aljazeera.com#13][abc.net.au#3]. The response follows President Trump’s threat to impose an additional 100% tariff on Chinese imports, potentially as soon as November 1, citing Beijing’s newly announced export curbs on rare-earth materials; he also signaled export controls on critical software by that date [lemonde.fr#6][lemonde.fr#7][abc.net.au#3][dawn.com#8][scmp.com#17]. Beijing defended its rare-earth restrictions as legitimate and linked them to recent US actions, including adding Chinese firms to a trade “黑</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/iWYnjF8UvYPH_HwRHUWXciWnwzDjmR5Jy7Q5D-8Oj1QbBib7HzBlY74BOolfPExXpYoHl_6Xug3NgRVtA0cE0GrsaMLgxagS1N50IxO2j6l8zpbHd1c7O2i_18qIUQ6qWfwtDKZk2C9GLuyRHoda-sIAzw6USD5E0AURJ58nK3Arps10Ln9gl2_WU2EmDhU7CqkNz8-we2eTsB0itawUJvo' alt='Containers stacked at Qingdao port as tariff tensions rise between the US and China.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>China’s message: Beijing said it does not want but is not afraid of a tariff war, called high-tariff threats the wrong approach, and vowed corresponding measures while defending its export curbs as legitimate [euronews.com#1][thehindu.com#2][aljazeera.com#13][dawn.com#8].</li><li>US rationale: President Trump framed China’s rare-earth export curbs as “extraordinarily aggressive” and threatened an additional 100% tariff that could take effect as soon as November 1 [abc.net.au#3][lemonde.fr#6][lemonde.fr#7].</li><li>Summit uncertainty: The renewed tension could derail a tentative Trump–Xi meeting later this month, and the President has threatened to cancel it [lemonde.fr#7][dawn.com#8].</li><li>Market jitters: Global equities fell on Friday and Chinese stocks&#x27;